  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A sonic boom is caused by the shock waves created when an object travels through the air at a speed greater than the speed of sound, known as supersonic speed. The speed of sound varies with atmospheric conditions, but it is approximately 343 meters per second (1,125 feet per second) at sea level and at 20 degrees Celsius (68 degrees Fahrenheit).\n\nWhen an object (like an aircraft) moves at supersonic speeds, it compresses the air in front of it, creating pressure waves. These waves build up and eventually merge into a single shock wave that travels outward from the object. As the shock wave reaches the ground, it produces a loud noise known as a sonic boom.\n\nKey factors that influence the intensity and characteristics of a sonic boom include:\n\n1. **Speed of the Object**: The faster the object is traveling above the speed of sound, the stronger the sonic boom.\n2. **Shape of the Object**: Aerodynamic shapes can influence how shock waves form and spread.\n3. **Altitude**: Higher altitudes can result in a different sound profile, as the shock wave is affected by the atmosphere's density.\n4. **Atmospheric Conditions**: Temperature, humidity, and wind can also affect the propagation of sound waves.\n\nThe perception of a sonic boom can vary based on distance from the flight path, with the boom often described as a double bang or thunder-like noise.",
